# 3. Problem Statement
Our target users are busy students and young adults who want affordable meals but struggle with planning, budgeting, and using what they already have. Nowadays, many people buy groceries with intentions of cooking, but then forget ingredients in the fridge or cupboard, leading to wasted food and money. Furthermore, when people don’t know what to cook, they revert to takeout or processed meals that can be more expensive and offtrack of health goals. Users also face real constraints that typical recipe apps don’t handle well, including allergies, dislikes, calorie targets, and limited time to cook or meal prep.

# 4. Why Now?
This problem matters even more in the next 3 to 5 years because food prices and personal budgets are becoming increasingly tight for many households, and food waste has become both a financial and environmental issue. At the same time, user expectations have changed: people now want personalized tools that adapt to them, not one size fits all meal plans. Technologically,  GPT-style language models have become more accessible to students and developers, and free recipe/nutrition datasets make it possible to build a working prototype without needing a private database. In recent years, meal prep and fitness/nutrition tracking have become mainstream, so a tool that can generate usable recipes and weekly prep plans from real constraints is relevant.

# 5. Proposed AI-Powered Solution
PantryPilot is an AI recipe generator and weekly meal-prep planner designed to reduce food waste and help users stay on budget. In one mode, the user types a list of ingredients they already have ( “eggs, spinach, rice, chicken, yogurt”) and the system returns recipes that use those ingredients as much as possible, along with reasonable substitutions when something is missing. In a second mode, the user inputs a weekly grocery budget plus preferences (foods/cuisines they like), allergy/exclusion information, and calorie targets, and the system returns a customized meal plan for the week with recipes and a shopping list that stays within the weekly budget.

AI adds value here because the hard part is not just matching ingredients to a recipe title; it’s generating step-by-step recipes and adapting them to the user (allergies, dislikes, calorie targets, time available, number of meals). Simple AI’s can filter ingredients, but they struggle to produce high quality instructions, smart substitutions, and variety across a full week. A generative model can create full recipes and instructions that are personalized while still following constraint checks.

# 6. Initial Technical Concept
We will need data that includes recipe ingredients, instructions and nutrition information per ingredient or per recipe. Our core model will be nanoGPT trained on recipe formatted text so it can generate complete recipes. Around the generative model, we will implement a constraint layer that enforces allergies/exclusions and helps focus the output on the users inputs. For the budget and calorie parts, we can use lightweight heuristics or a small optimization step: estimate cost from a simple price table and estimate calories from a nutrition database, then select a set of meals that fits the user’s weekly budget and calorie targets.

Our nanoGPT work directly feeds into the product by becoming the custom generative component that produces full recipes in a consistent format and style. During the nanoGPT milestone, we will evaluate different model configurations and training setups, then apply what we learn (stability, loss curves, output quality, overfitting signs) to decide the best tradeoff for recipe generation in the MVP. We will also use sample generations as an evaluation tool: if a config produces clearer ingredient lists and more consistent step ordering, that config becomes the base for PantryPilot.

# 7. Scope for MVP
In 6 weeks, we can realistically build a working prototype that runs locally and is easy to demo from our GitHub repo. This demo will focus on a model that demonstrates both goals: using pantry ingredients to reduce waste, and generating a weekly plan under a user-entered weekly budget.

V1 feature: A user can enter (1) a  list of pantry ingredients, (2) a weekly grocery budget, (3) allergies/exclusions, (4) preference notes, and (5) a calorie target and number of days, and our system returns (a) a set of complete nanoGPT-generated recipes, (b) a weekly meal plan, and (c) a shopping list with an estimated total cost that is designed to stay within the weekly budget.

# 8. Risks and Open Questions
A top unknown is data quality and formatting: recipes come in many styles, and we need a clean, consistent list for training nanoGPT to generate full recipes that are readable and usable. A second major risk is safety and correctness for allergies and dietary restrictions, because generative models can mistake ingredients; we must enforce hard constraint checks and output validation to reduce the chance of unsafe suggestions. A third open question is how accurately we can make budget and calorie estimates with limited time: prices vary widely and nutrition values depend on serving sizes.

# 9. Planned Data Sources
We plan to use open recipe datasets from sources. For calories and nutrient estimates, we can use a public nutrition database. For budgeting, the MVP can start with a small, editable price table (CSV) for common ingredients to estimate weekly grocery costs, and we can optionally supplement it with synthetic price data for missing items. All data sources and any preprocessing steps will be documented in the repo with links and licensing notes.
